A: The problem description does not say that the gcd of two consecutive numbers should be 1.  So the minimum answer is 2.  And that is a valid answer.  So we need a check to see whether a number is a single-number segment.
You can make one little optimization to avoid looping over the same part multiple times.  For the i-th number (call it x), compute the minimum segment length and gcd from the start of the array to the i-th number.  Now if that length is less than the minimum length seen so far, compute the gcd of x with the gcd_all computed from the numbers from 0 to i-1, and see whether the minimum of the two lengths is the minimum answer for all numbers up to i.
class Solution {
public:
    int minOperations(vector<int> &nums) {
        int n = nums.size(), gcd_all = 0, cnt1 = 0;
        for (int x: nums) {
            gcd_all = gcd(gcd_all, x);
            if (x == 1) ++cnt1;
        }
        if (gcd_all > 1) return -1;
        if (cnt1) return n - cnt1;
        int min_size = n, g = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            g = gcd(g, nums[i]);
            if (g == 1) {
                min_size = min(min_size, i+1-gcd(gcd_all, nums[i-1]));
                g = 0;
            }
        }
        return min_size + n - 1;
    }
};

